1. Problem Context

¶

We are a bank that has a database with a large amount of information about our customers.
Our goal is to help analysts predict the churn rate of these customers to reduce it.

Against this dataset, we can capture up-to-date information that can determine the long-term
stability of the account or its imminent exit.

1.1. Business Understanding¶

The aim is to analyze a bank's customer data to understand the causes that lead customers to abandon the financial institution and,
consequently, to seek solutions to avoid it. The importance of preventing customer churn lies in maintaining a solid base of loyal
customers, which is essential for the bank's long-term growth and profitability.

  • Definition of the objective: Help analysts predict the churn rate of these customers to reduce it.

1.2. Analytic Approach¶

  • The technical definition of the objective: Create a predictive classification model to classify data from the testing file.
    We train the model with the training data and seek to maximize the F1 (macro) score.

1.3 Data Content¶

Column Description
CLIENTNUM Unique identifier for each customer (Integer)
Attrition_Flag Indicator of whether the customer has churned or stayed (Boolean)
Customer_Age Age of the customer (Integer)
Gender Gender of the customer (String)
Dependent_count Number of dependents the customer has (Integer)
Education_Level Customer's education level (String)
Marital_Status Marital status of the customer (String)
Income_Category Customer's income category (String)
Card_Category Type of card held by the customer (String)
Months_on_book Time the customer has been on the books (Integer)
Total_Relationship_Count Total number of relationships the customer has with the credit card provider (Integer)
Months_Inactive_12_mon Number of months the customer has been inactive in the last twelve months (Integer)
Contacts_Count_12_mon Number of contacts the customer has had in the last twelve months (Integer)
Credit_Limit Customer's credit limit (Integer)
Total_Revolving_Bal Total revolving balance of the customer (Integer)
Avg_Open_To_Buy Average open to buy ratio of the customer (Integer)
Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 Total amount changed from quarter 4 to quarter 1 (Integer)
Total_Trans_Amt Total transaction amount (Integer)
Total_Trans_Ct Total transaction count (Integer)
Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1 Total count changed from quarter 4 to quarter 1 (Integer)
Avg_Utilization_Ratio Average utilization ratio of the customer (Integer)

Is the data missing for random reasons or are there reasons behind such absences?

Some of the reasons why such data may be unknown are:

  1. Privacy related: It may be that the bank does not have the explicit consent of the customer to collect and use such data,
    and it may not be included in the database.

  2. In relation to verification: Customers may not provide complete or accurate information about their educational level,
    marital status or income, which makes verification difficult.

  3. Change of circumstances: Information about the client may change over time. For example, a client who was married when he/she opened his/her bank account
    may have divorced and not updated his/her marital status in the bank's records.

In [269]:
def drop_rows_cols(df):
  df.columns = df.columns.str.replace('|'.join(['train_idx','test_idx']), 'idx')
  df.drop(['idx','CLIENTNUM'], axis=1, inplace=True)
  df.drop(df[(df['Marital_Status'] == 'Unknown') & (df['Income_Category'] == 'Unknown') & (df['Education_Level'] == 'Unknown')]\
          .index, axis=0, inplace=True)
  return df

train = drop_rows_cols(train)

What types of missing values ​​do we have?
  • The absence of data on both the `Education level` and the `Marital status` of the person, appear to be independent of both
    the observed and unobserved variables, and occur completely randomly (MCAR).

  • The absence of data in the `Income category` seems to be conditional on the observed values. (MAR).

    • How ​​will we handle them?

    • We'll treat Unknown categories just like that, and treat it like an other category.

Insights:

  • Months_Inactive_12_mon. Very few customers have been inactive for 4 or more months (there are also
    very few with 0 months of inactivity, but it's normal not to have activity for 100% of the months).

  • Contacts_Count_12_mon. There are very few customers with more than 4 contacts with the bank, just as there
    are very few with 0 contacts.

  • Credit_Limit. TIt exhibits a long-tailed distribution, which is reasonable because fewer people have access to
    higher credit limits. The abrupt increase towards the end may be due to the bank's limit cap, representing all customers who
    have reached that cap.

  • Total_Revolving_Bal The majority of customers have no outstanding balance. Another detail is that
    despite having customers with high credit limits, none of them have a balance exceeding 2517. There might be a cap at that point,
    explaining the sharp increase.

  • Avg_Open_To_Buy. The values in this column result from subtracting the total account balance from the credit limit.
    Therefore, given the presence of customers with atypical credit limits, it's normal to see a similar number of customers
    with atypical values here.

  • Total_Trans_Amt. Some customers have very high transaction totals

  • Total_Amt_Chng_Q4_Q1 & Total_Ct_Chng_Q4_Q1. The proportion of customers with atypical values in the amount changed from
    the 4th quarter to the 1st quarter is nearly the same as in the count. It's likely that these are the same records.

  • Avg_Utilization_Ratio. This metric is based on the revolving balance divided by the credit limit. With the explanations
    given above about the other two variables, its behavior can be understood.

categorical_features = train.select_dtypes('object')
def groupby_categorical(feature):
  group = train.groupby('Attrition_Flag')[feature].value_counts(normalize=True)
  return group.unstack()

for i, feature in enumerate(categorical_features):
    if i < 5:
        row, col = i // 3, i % 3
        group = groupby_categorical(feature)
        ax = axes[row, col]
        group.plot(kind='bar', color=sns.color_palette('mako_r',len(group.columns)), xlabel=f'Attrition_Flag group by {feature}', ax=ax)
        ax.set_ylabel('Percentage')
        ax.set_title(f'Attrition_Flag vs {feature}')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Insight:
    I don't see any characteristic that is significantly more prevalent in one group compared to the other.
    Therefore, at this moment, I don't have enough evidence to conclude that the categorical variables, most of
    which are demographic in nature, can be potential predictors of whether a customer will leave the institution.

Can I determine which categorical variables are more statistically related to the target variable?

We can create a contingency table for each categorical column alongside the target variable Attrition_Flag,
and then apply a chi-squared test to observe the p-value.

Our hypotheses are as follows:

  • H0: There is no significant relationship between the categorical variables and the target variable, meaning that
    categorical variables do not influence the probability of the target variable being 0 or 1.

  • H1: There is a significant relationship between the categorical variables and the target variable, suggesting that
    categorical variables do influence the probability of the target variable being 0 or 1.

In [279]:
for catcol in train_eda.select_dtypes('object'):
  gdf = train_eda.groupby('Attrition_Flag')[catcol].value_counts().unstack().values
  res = chi2_contingency(gdf)
  print(f'category: {catcol}, statistic: {res.statistic:.4f}, pvalue: {res.pvalue:.4f}')

category: Gender, statistic: 17.9721, pvalue: 0.0000
category: Education_Level, statistic: 17.7253, pvalue: 0.0070
category: Marital_Status, statistic: 2.6401, pvalue: 0.4505
category: Income_Category, statistic: 11.6446, pvalue: 0.0400
category: Card_Category, statistic: 5.1505, pvalue: 0.1611
Significant variables:
  • Gender < 0.0000
  • Education_Level = 0.007
  • Income_Category = 0.04

    • With a p-value less than 0.05, it suggests a significant relationship between these categorical variables
    and the target variable. In other words, categorical variables do influence the probability of the target
    variable being 0 or 1. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis for these categories and accept the
    alternative hypothesis.

    We will take this information into account for subsequent stages when constructing the prediction model.

3.3.2 Numeric variables & Target¶

What information about the customer is most correlated with the abandonment rate?

In [280]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(train_eda.corr(), dtype=bool))
sns.heatmap(train_eda.corr(), annot=True, cmap='vlag_r', fmt='.2f', cbar=False, mask=mask)
plt.show()
Insights:
  • We observe a high correlation between the variables Total_Revolving_Bal & Avg_Utilization_Ratio.
    This correlation is logical since the calculation of the utilization ratio includes the revolving balance as the numerator.

  • A similar scenario arises with Credit_Limit & Avg_Open_To_Buy, but in this case, the credit limit acts as the subtracted
    value in the formula.

  • Total_Trans_Amt & Total_Trans_Ct exhibit a strong correlation. This can be attributed to the fact that, with a higher number
    of transactions, it is expected that the total transaction amount will also be higher.

  • There is also a notable correlation between the variables Customer_Age & Months_on_Book. However, in this case, I couldn't
    identify a clear cause-and-effect relationship.

    • We are aware of the importance of carefully selecting relevant variables to avoid negative effects such as overfitting and poor performance
    on new data. Nevertheless, sometimes having more variables in a classification model can offer benefits such as the ability to identify
    complex patterns, reduced bias, and increased flexibility. In this case, when testing both approaches, the test set yielded better results
    when including a larger number of variables.

4. Preprocess Data

¶

In [284]:
train['Attrition_Flag'] = train['Attrition_Flag'].astype(int)

# Drop the same rows and columns for the test dataset
drop_rows_cols(test)

# Separate X and Y in the train dataset
X = train.drop('Attrition_Flag', axis=1)
y_train = train.loc[:,'Attrition_Flag']

# StandardScaler for numerical columns
sc = StandardScaler()
X_train_num = sc.fit_transform(X.select_dtypes('number'))
X_test_num = sc.fit_transform(test.select_dtypes('number'))

# OneHotEncoder for categorical columns
ohe = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore', drop='first', sparse_output=False)
X_train_str = ohe.fit_transform(X.select_dtypes(exclude='number'))
X_test_str = ohe.transform(test.select_dtypes(exclude='number'))

# Column names
column_names = sc.feature_names_in_.tolist() + ohe.get_feature_names_out().tolist()

# Concatenate the datasets
X_train = pd.DataFrame(np.c_[X_train_num,X_train_str], columns=column_names)
X_test = pd.DataFrame(np.c_[X_test_num,X_test_str], columns=column_names)

We'll split the training dataset into one for testing, one for validation to tune hyperparameters, and another for actual training.

5. Modeling

¶

For the churn prediction task, it's crucial to choose the appropriate classification algorithm.
Among the algorithms we will evaluate are logistic regression, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting.
Each of them has strengths and weaknesses in terms of complexity, ability to handle large and complex
datasets, model interpretability, and required accuracy.

We will utilize the "F1 score (macro)" (as mentioned at the beginning of the project) to gauge how well
the model predicts, and additionally, we will create a confusion matrix to visualize the outcomes.

In [326]:
def display_cv_results(model):
    print("Best hyperparameters: ",model.best_params_)
    print("Best score :",np.round(model.best_score_,4))
    print("Average score: ",np.round(np.nanmean(model.cv_results_['mean_test_score']),4))
    print("Average Standard Deviation of scores: ",np.round(np.nanstd(model.cv_results_['mean_test_score']),4))

5.3 Gradient Booster¶

Gradient Boosting is an accurate technique and capable of handling complex and large data sets,
making it ideal for binary classification problems. Additionally, it can handle missing data and outliers,
and is able to identify important features in the data.

For more information you can consult more information in the scikit-learn documentation:
https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.GradientBoostingClassifier.html

6. Conclusions & Submission

In conclusion, this data science project delved into customer churn rate analysis within a bank,
encompassing the construction and evaluation of multiple classification models, including logistic
regression, random forest, and gradient boosting. RandomizedSearchCV was employed for hyperparameter
optimization in each model, followed by a validation test to assess performance on unseen data.

Subsequently, an evaluation test on a separate dataset was conducted to compare model performances.
Notably, the gradient boosting model outperformed the other two models in terms of precision and F1-score
in both tests. In summary, this project underscores the potential of the gradient boosting model as a valuable
tool for predicting customer churn rates in a bank, facilitating proactive measures for customer retention.

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
